'''Pacific Centennial Oscillation''' is a [[climate oscillation]] predicted by some [[climate model]]s.

In the [[Pacific Ocean]], variability in [[sea surface temperature]]s is an important influence on precipitation regimens in the [[Americas]] and how this variability changes in response to [[anthropogenic climate change]] ([[El Nino]]-like or [[La Nina]]-like) may determine the outcome of climate change.{{sfn|Karnauskas|Smerdon|Seager|González-Rouco|2012|p=5943}} The sea surface temperature patterns may fluctuate over thousands or millions of years and determining trends and patterns from observational data is difficult.{{sfn|Karnauskas|Smerdon|Seager|González-Rouco|2012|p=5944}}

Several climate models have shown the existence of a centennial scale cycle in [[Pacific Ocean]] temperatures, with fluctuations of about {{convert|0.5|C}}{{sfn|Karnauskas|Smerdon|Seager|González-Rouco|2012|p=5958}} and most temperature changes concentrated below the surface of the [[Western Pacific Ocean|Western Pacific]]. The predicted effects have some similarities to [[El Nino Southern Oscillation]]{{sfn|Karnauskas|Smerdon|Seager|González-Rouco|2012|p=5943}} and may be responsible for recent [[La Nina]]-like trends in Pacific Ocean temperature patterns{{sfn|Coats|Smerdon|Cook|Seager|2015|p=125}} and trends in the east-west gradient of Pacific sea surface temperatures from 1900 forward;{{sfn|Samanta|Karnauskas|Goodkin|Coats|2018|pp=10609-10610}} in one climate model the Pacific Centennial Oscillation drives long [[drought]]s in the [[Southwestern United States]]{{sfn|Coats|Smerdon|Cook|Seager|2015|p=136}} such as the [[2011–2017 California drought]].<ref name="Seager2015" />

The Pacific Centennial Oscillation cycle however might be spurious,{{sfn|Karnauskas|Smerdon|Seager|González-Rouco|2012|p=5959}} a model [[artifact (error)|artifact]].{{sfn|Samanta|Karnauskas|Goodkin|Coats|2018|p=10610}} Later research has shown the possibility that centennial cycles in the Pacific Ocean sea surface temperature structure can be a consequence of an overly long Pacific [[cold tongue]], although genuine centennial cycles in nature cannot be completely ruled out.{{sfn|Samanta|Karnauskas|Goodkin|Coats|2018|p=10616}}

